[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":893},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Freact\u002F2022\u002F09\u002F23\u002Flearn-react-09-usecontext\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Freact\u002F2022\u002F09\u002F23\u002Flearn-react-09-usecontext\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Freact\u002F2022\u002F09\u002F23\u002Flearn-react-09-usecontext\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Freact\u002F2022\u002F09\u002F23\u002Flearn-react-09-usecontext\u002F":870,"related:\u002Fen\u002Freact\u002F2022\u002F09\u002F23\u002Flearn-react-09-usecontext\u002F":879},"\u002Freact\u002F20220923\u002F1533941335\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":853,"date":854,"description":855,"extension":856,"lang":857,"meta":858,"navigation":95,"path":859,"readingMinutes":860,"seo":861,"standalone":862,"stem":863,"tags":864,"tldr":867,"updated":854,"url":868,"__hash__":869},"content\u002Fen\u002FReact\u002Flearn-react-09-usecontext.md","You'll Learn React Eventually, So Why Not Now? - React Basics - useContext - (9)","1003112170",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":847},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,27,34,49,52,55,336,347,375,378,394,403,407,413,516,521,527,560,573,690,695,704,713,781,789,791,794,800,809,812,825,829,832,843],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"In the earlier chapters we got a first look at how React passes data between components — that's Props. The thing is, Props usually flow from the top all the way down. That keeps your data flow predictable since it's one-directional, but it also brings along some annoying problems, mainly: passing data too deep. So this is the point where we meet something new — useContext.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"passing-data-with-props","Passing Data With Props",[17,25,26],{},"For normal day-to-day work, most of us just use Props to pass data downward. So let me throw up a quick diagram to recap how Props flowed in the earlier chapters.",[17,28,29],{},[30,31],"img",{"alt":32,"src":33},"props passing through three layers","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002Fithelp2022-react\u002F2022-09-01%2022.25.05.png",[17,35,36,37,41,42,45,46,48],{},"From the image above you can see that Props has to be passed three times before the data finally reaches ",[38,39,40],"code",{},"Button",". That causes a fair bit of pain when you're building and maintaining things. For example: we're not even sure the ",[38,43,44],{},"List"," component needs to receive Props at all, but it's forced to accept them just so the data can keep traveling down to ",[38,47,40],{},". Stuff like that comes up all the time, which is why in real-world work you pretty often need a way for components to talk to each other across the tree.",[17,50,51],{},"Let me show you some actual example code — maybe that'll make it click a bit more?",[17,53,54],{},"Here's the example:",[56,57,62],"pre",{"className":58,"code":59,"language":60,"meta":61,"style":61},"language-jsx shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","const Button = ({ data }) => {\n  const pay = () => {\n    window.alert(`你已成功購買 ${data.title}`);\n  }\n\n  return (\n    \u003Cbutton type=\"button\" onClick={ pay }>點我購買({ data.price } $)\u003C\u002Fbutton>\n  )\n}\n\nconst Card = ({ data }) => {\n  return (\n    \u003Cdiv>\n      \u003Ch5>產品名稱：{ data.title }\u003C\u002Fh5>\n      \u003CButton data={ data }\u002F>\n    \u003C\u002Fdiv>\n  )\n}\n\n\nconst Products = () => {\n  const [ data, setData ] = React.useState({\n    title: 'PlayStation5',\n    price: 75000,\n  });\n\n  return (\n    \u003Cdiv>\n      \u003Cul>\n        \u003Cli key={ data.title }>\n          \u003CCard data={ data } \u002F>\n        \u003C\u002Fli>\n      \u003C\u002Ful>\n    \u003C\u002Fdiv>\n  )\n}\n\nconst App = () => {\n  return (\n    \u003Cdiv>\n      \u003CProducts \u002F>\n    \u003C\u002Fdiv>\n  )\n}\n\nconst app = document.querySelector('#app');\nconst root = ReactDOM.createRoot(app);\nroot.render(\u003CApp \u002F>);\n","jsx","",[38,63,64,72,78,84,90,97,103,109,1